var tafsirData_23 = {
  1: {
    "Successful indeed are the believers": "Allah begins this chapter with a powerful declaration of good news. The word 'successful' means those who have attained victory, prosperity, and eternal happiness. This success is not worldly success like wealth or fame, but the ultimate success—being saved from Hellfire and entering Paradise. The believers are those who have true faith in their hearts, and Allah is announcing that they have already achieved success in His sight. This is meant to encourage the believers and give them hope that their faith and efforts are not in vain. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said that when this verse was revealed, he said: 'Ten verses have been revealed to me, whoever acts upon them will enter Paradise' (Tirmidhi). This shows that the following qualities are a roadmap to eternal success."
  },
  2: {
    "those who humble themselves in prayer": "The first quality of successful believers is humility and focus in prayer. Khushoo (humility) means the heart is fully present and attentive to Allah during prayer. It involves stillness of the body, focus of the mind, and submission of the heart. When you pray with khushoo, you are not thinking about your work, your phone, or your problems—you are standing before the King of all kings. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Pray as if you see Allah, and if you cannot see Him, know that He sees you' (Bukhari). Imagine if you were meeting a president or a king—you would be fully attentive. How much more attentive should we be when standing before Allah? This quality is mentioned first because prayer is the most important act of worship after faith itself."
  },
  3: {
    "those who avoid idle talk": "The second quality is turning away from anything that has no benefit—whether it is speech, actions, or gatherings. Idle talk includes gossip, backbiting, vulgar jokes, arguments that lead nowhere, and wasting time on useless entertainment. A true believer values their time and knows that every moment is a chance to earn rewards from Allah. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Part of a person's being a good Muslim is leaving alone that which does not concern him' (Tirmidhi). This does not mean you cannot relax or have fun, but it means avoiding things that are sinful or that waste your precious time. Successful believers focus their energy on what benefits them in this life and the next."
  },
  4: {
    "those who pay alms-tax": "The third quality is giving zakah, which is the obligatory charity that purifies wealth. Zakah means 'purification' and 'growth.' When you give zakah, you purify your wealth from greed and your soul from selfishness, and Allah blesses and increases what remains. It is typically 2.5% of your savings given to the poor and needy. This quality shows that successful believers are not attached to their wealth; they understand that everything belongs to Allah and they are just caretakers. Giving zakah also strengthens the community by helping those in need. The Prophet (peace be upon him) warned that those who do not pay zakah will face severe punishment on the Day of Judgment. So successful believers are generous and fulfill their financial obligations to Allah."
  },
  5: {
    "those who guard their chastity": "The fourth quality is protecting oneself from unlawful sexual relations. This means controlling one's desires and avoiding anything that leads to immorality—whether it is looking at forbidden things, inappropriate relationships, or actual adultery and fornication. In a world filled with temptations, this quality is especially important. Guarding one's chastity protects the individual, preserves family honor, and maintains the moral fabric of society. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Whoever guarantees me what is between his jaws (tongue) and what is between his legs (private parts), I guarantee him Paradise' (Bukhari). This shows how important self-control is in achieving success."
  },
  6: {
    "except with their wives or those ˹bondwomen˺ in their possession": "Allah clarifies that there is no blame in having intimate relations within the boundaries He has set—which is marriage. Islam does not forbid intimacy; it channels it into a blessed and halal relationship. The mention of 'those in their possession' refers to a historical context of bondwomen, which was regulated and eventually phased out. The key point is that Allah has provided a lawful way to fulfill human desires.",
    "for then they are free from blame": "When a person fulfills their desires through the halal means Allah has provided, they are not sinning; in fact, they are rewarded for it. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that even fulfilling your desire with your spouse is charity (Muslim). This shows that Islam is a balanced religion that does not suppress natural desires but directs them toward what is good."
  },
  7: {
    "but whoever seeks beyond that are the transgressors": "Anyone who seeks to fulfill their desires outside of what Allah has permitted is crossing the boundaries set by Allah. They are transgressors and sinners. This includes adultery, fornication, homosexuality, and any other form of sexual immorality. Allah is making it absolutely clear that there is no gray area here—the boundaries are set, and crossing them leads to punishment. This is a stern warning to protect individuals and society from the harms that come with sexual immorality, such as broken families, diseases, and spiritual destruction."
  },
  8: {
    "˹the believers are also˺ those who are true to their trusts and covenants": "The fifth quality is being trustworthy and keeping promises. A trust (amanah) can be anything entrusted to you—money, secrets, responsibilities, or even your own body and abilities which Allah has given you. A covenant includes promises you make to others and the covenant between you and Allah. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'The signs of a hypocrite are three: when he speaks he lies, when he promises he breaks it, and when he is trusted he betrays' (Bukhari and Muslim). A true believer is the opposite—they are reliable, honest, and keep their word. Whether it is a business deal, a marriage contract, or simply promising to meet someone at a certain time, believers honor their commitments."
  },
  9: {
    "and those who are ˹properly˺ observant of their prayers": "The sixth quality brings us back to prayer, emphasizing its importance. While verse 2 mentioned humility IN prayer, this verse mentions being observant OF prayers—meaning praying consistently at their proper times without missing them. This includes praying the five daily prayers on time and fulfilling all their conditions properly. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'The first thing a person will be asked about on the Day of Judgment is their prayer' (Abu Dawud). If the prayer is in order, the rest will be in order. Notice that prayer is mentioned at the beginning and end of this list, forming a framework around all the other qualities, showing how central it is to a believer's life."
  },
  10: {
    "These are the ones who will be awarded": "After listing all these beautiful qualities, Allah now announces the reward. The word 'inherit' is used, which is significant. When you inherit something, you receive it as your right, and it becomes permanently yours. Just as a person inherits wealth from their family, the believers will inherit Paradise. The Prophet (peace be upon him) explained that everyone has a place in Paradise and a place in Hell; the believers will inherit the places in Paradise that were prepared for the disbelievers who rejected faith (Muslim). What a tremendous honor and reward for those who embody these qualities!"
  },
  11: {
    "Paradise as their own": "Specifically, they will inherit Al-Firdaws, which is the highest and most central part of Paradise. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'When you ask Allah for Paradise, ask Him for Al-Firdaws, for it is the highest part of Paradise, in the middle of Paradise, and from it spring the rivers of Paradise, and above it is the Throne of the Most Merciful' (Bukhari). This is the best of the best.",
    "They will be there forever": "And this inheritance is not temporary—they will live in this bliss forever, never dying, never getting sick, never getting bored, never being expelled. Eternal happiness with no end. This is the ultimate success that Allah promised at the beginning of the chapter, and now we see what it truly means."
  },
  12: {
    "And indeed, We created humankind from an extract of clay": "Allah now shifts to discussing the origin of human creation as evidence of His power and as proof that resurrection is possible. The first human, Adam (peace be upon him), was created from clay—earth. This is our humble origin. An 'extract' means the finest and purest part of something. Allah took the essence of clay from the earth and created from it the father of humanity. This should make us humble, knowing we come from dirt, yet grateful that Allah honored us and gave us such high status among His creation. The fact that Allah created something so complex and intelligent as a human from simple clay shows His infinite power."
  },
  13: {
    "then placed each ˹human˺ as a sperm-drop in a secure place": "While Adam was created from clay, his descendants are created through reproduction. The sperm-drop (nutfah) is placed in the mother's womb, which Allah describes as a 'secure place.' The womb is perfectly designed to protect and nourish the developing baby—it has the right temperature, the right nutrients, and is shielded from harm. Think about how amazing this is: a tiny drop, invisible to the naked eye, contains all the information needed to create a complete human being with eyes, ears, brain, heart, and trillions of cells. This secure place nurtures this drop until it becomes a fully formed human. Who designed this system? Only Allah, the Most Wise."
  },
  14: {
    "then We developed the drop into a clinging clot ˹of blood˺": "The sperm-drop transforms into an 'alaqah'—something that clings, like a leech, and also resembles a blood clot. At this stage, the embryo attaches to the wall of the uterus. Modern science confirms this description with remarkable accuracy, even though the Quran was revealed over 1400 years ago when no microscopes existed.",
    "then developed the clot into a lump ˹of flesh˺": "The next stage is 'mudghah,' which literally means something that has been chewed—like a piece of gum with teeth marks. The embryo at this stage looks exactly like this, with the somites (early vertebrae) resembling teeth marks. Again, this matches what embryologists discovered only recently.",
    "then developed the lump into bones": "The lump of flesh then develops into bones. The skeletal system begins to form, giving structure to the body. This is the framework upon which everything else is built.",
    "then clothed the bones with flesh": "After the bones form, muscles and flesh wrap around them, just like clothing covers a body. This sequence—bones first, then flesh—is exactly what modern embryology confirms. The precision of the Quran is a sign for those who reflect.",
    "then We brought it into being as a new creation": "Finally, Allah breathes the soul into this physical form, and it becomes a completely new creation—a living human being with consciousness, emotions, and the ability to think and choose. This transformation from a drop of fluid to a thinking, feeling human is nothing short of miraculous.",
    "So Blessed is Allah, the Best of Creators": "Allah concludes this description by praising Himself. No one can create like Allah. Human beings can make things from existing materials, but only Allah creates from nothing and designs with such perfection. Reflecting on our own creation should fill us with awe and gratitude."
  },
  15: {
    "After that you will surely die": "Despite all this amazing creation and development, every human will eventually die. This is a certainty that no one can escape. No matter how wealthy, powerful, or healthy you are, death will come. This verse serves as a wake-up call—life is temporary. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Remember frequently the destroyer of pleasures: death' (Tirmidhi). This is not meant to make us depressed, but to motivate us to prepare for what comes after."
  },
  16: {
    "then on the Day of Judgment you will be resurrected": "Death is not the end. Allah will resurrect every human being on the Day of Judgment to be held accountable for their deeds. The same Allah who created you the first time from clay and a drop of fluid can certainly bring you back to life. If you doubt resurrection, just look at your own creation—isn't the One who created you from nothing capable of recreating you? This is the logical conclusion of the passage: creation, death, resurrection, and accountability. This is the purpose of our existence."
  },
  17: {
    "And indeed, We created above you seven levels ˹of heaven˺": "After discussing the creation of humans, Allah directs our attention to the heavens above. He created seven heavens, one above another, in perfect order and harmony. These vast structures are beyond our imagination in their size and complexity. The first heaven alone contains billions of galaxies, each with billions of stars. And there are six more beyond it! This shows the unimaginable power and majesty of Allah.",
    "We are never unmindful of ˹Our˺ creation": "Allah is not distant or uninvolved. He is fully aware of everything in His creation—every creature, every event, every thought. Nothing escapes His knowledge or care. He provides for His creation, maintains the systems that sustain life, and watches over everything. This is comforting for believers: Allah knows your struggles, your prayers, and your efforts. He has not forgotten you."
  },
  18: {
    "We send down rain from the sky in perfect measure": "Allah sends rain in exact amounts—not too much to cause floods, not too little to cause drought (in most cases, as a general blessing). This precise measurement is part of Allah's wisdom and mercy. The water cycle that we learn about in science—evaporation, condensation, precipitation—is all designed and controlled by Allah.",
    "causing it to soak into the earth": "The rain doesn't just fall and disappear; Allah causes it to be absorbed into the earth where it is stored in underground reservoirs (aquifers) and feeds wells and springs. This water sustains life even during dry seasons. Think about how perfectly this system works to provide continuous water supply.",
    "And We are surely able to take it away": "This is a warning. The same Allah who provides water can take it away. If He withdrew this blessing, all life would perish. We should never take water for granted or be ungrateful for it. Some communities around the world suffer from severe water shortages, which reminds us of how precious this blessing is."
  },
  19: {
    "With it We produce for you gardens of palm trees and grapevines": "With this water, Allah causes gardens to grow. Palm trees and grapevines are specifically mentioned because they were highly valued in Arabia and the Mediterranean region, providing staple foods, drinks, and economic benefits. Dates from palm trees are nutritious and can be stored for long periods, making them essential for survival.",
    "in which there are abundant fruits": "These gardens don't just have one or two types of fruit, but abundant varieties—all for human benefit and enjoyment. Allah could have made all food bland and similar, but He created variety and delicious flavors out of His mercy.",
    "and from which you may eat": "All of this is for you to eat and benefit from. Allah is pointing out His generosity and care for humanity. Every bite of fruit you eat is a gift from Allah that should remind you of His blessings."
  },
  20: {
    "as well as ˹olive˺ trees which grow at Mount Sinai": "The olive tree is highlighted here, specifically mentioning Mount Sinai where they grow abundantly. Mount Sinai is a blessed location where Allah spoke to Prophet Moses (peace be upon him). The olive tree is mentioned in multiple places in the Quran and is one of the most blessed trees.",
    "providing oil and a condiment to eat": "Olives provide oil which has countless uses—cooking, lighting lamps, skincare, and medicine. It is also eaten as food, adding flavor to meals. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Eat olive oil and use it on your hair and skin, for it comes from a blessed tree' (Tirmidhi). One tree provides so many benefits—this is from Allah's perfect design."
  },
  21: {
    "And there is certainly a lesson for you in cattle": "Allah calls us to reflect on cattle (camels, cows, sheep, goats) as signs of His power and blessings. The word 'lesson' (ibrah) means something to learn from and reflect upon. These animals are evidence of Allah's creative power and His care for humanity.",
    "from whose bellies We give you ˹milk˺ to drink": "Think about milk—it comes from between blood and digested food in the animal's body, yet it emerges pure, white, and nutritious. Allah says in another verse: 'Pure milk, pleasant to drink' (16:66). This transformation from grass to milk is a miracle we often overlook.",
    "and in them are many other benefits for you": "Beyond milk, cattle provide wool for clothing, leather for various uses, manure for fuel and fertilizer, and their labor for farming and transportation. Every part of these animals has been designed to benefit humans.",
    "and from them you may eat": "And their meat is halal for us to eat, providing protein and nourishment. All these blessings from one category of animals—and we rarely stop to thank Allah for them."
  },
  22: {
    "And you are carried upon ˹some of˺ them and upon ships": "Finally, Allah mentions transportation. Some animals like camels, horses, and donkeys carry people and goods from place to place. Ships carry people across seas and oceans. Before modern vehicles, these were the only means of travel and trade. Even today, ships transport most of the world's goods. Allah designed animals strong enough to carry loads and gave humans the knowledge to build ships. Both are blessings that facilitate human life and civilization. This completes a beautiful picture of Allah's comprehensive care for humanity—from creation, to sustenance, to transportation."
  },
  23: {
    "Indeed, We sent Noah to his people": "Allah now begins telling the story of Prophet Noah (Nuh, peace be upon him), one of the greatest messengers. He was the first messenger sent to humanity after people began worshipping idols. He lived among his people for 950 years, patiently calling them to Allah. His story is mentioned in multiple places in the Quran as a lesson for all generations.",
    "He declared, \"O my people! Worship Allah ˹alone˺\"": "Noah's message was simple and clear—the same message of all prophets: worship Allah alone. He addressed them lovingly as 'my people,' showing his care and connection to them. He wasn't a stranger imposing foreign ideas; he was one of them, wanting good for them.",
    "You have no god other than Him": "This is the core of Tawheed (Islamic monotheism). There is no deity worthy of worship except Allah. All the idols they carved and prayed to were false gods with no power to help or harm. This message challenged their entire way of life and the traditions of their ancestors.",
    "Will you not then fear ˹Him˺?": "Noah ends with a question to make them think: Will you not have taqwa (fear and consciousness of Allah)? Will you not protect yourselves from His punishment by obeying Him? This is not fear that paralyzes, but fear that motivates good behavior—like how fear of failing an exam motivates a student to study."
  },
  24: {
    "But the disbelieving chiefs of his people said ˹to the masses˺": "The opposition came primarily from the elite, the wealthy, and the powerful—those who benefited from the existing corrupt system. They didn't want change because they would lose their status and control. Throughout history, it has often been the arrogant elite who reject prophets while the humble and poor accept the truth.",
    "\"This is only a human like you, who wants to be superior to you\"": "Their first argument was that Noah was just a man like them. They couldn't accept that God would send a human messenger. This shows their flawed understanding—they expected angels or supernatural beings. But Allah sends human messengers because humans can relate to them and follow their example. They also accused Noah of having selfish motives, claiming he just wanted power and status. This is a common tactic of disbelievers: attack the messenger's character when you can't refute the message.",
    "Had Allah willed, He could have easily sent down angels ˹instead˺": "They argued that if Allah really wanted to send a message, He would send angels, not humans. But this misses the wisdom of Allah's plan. Angels cannot serve as role models for humans because they don't have human desires and struggles. A human prophet shows us that following Allah's commands is achievable for us too.",
    "We have never heard of this in ˹the history of˺ our forefathers": "Their second argument was blind following of tradition. 'Our ancestors didn't do this, so it must be wrong.' This is a dangerous mindset—judging truth by what your ancestors did rather than by evidence and reason. The Quran repeatedly criticizes this attitude. Just because something is old or traditional doesn't make it right."
  },
  25: {
    "He is simply insane": "When their logical arguments failed, they resorted to personal attacks and mockery. They called Prophet Noah insane. This is a pattern we see throughout history—when people cannot refute the truth, they attack the person bringing it. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) was also called a madman, a poet, and a magician by those who rejected his message. But history has shown who was truly guided and who was astray.",
    "so bear with him for a while": "They told the people to just wait and ignore Noah, assuming his 'madness' would pass or he would eventually give up. Little did they know that Noah would continue calling them for 950 years! And in the end, they were the ones destroyed while Noah and the believers were saved. This is a lesson for believers: patience and perseverance in truth will always triumph. The mockers of today may become the destroyed of tomorrow if they don't repent."
  },
  26: {
    "Noah prayed, \"My Lord! Help me, because they have denied ˹me˺.\"": "After 950 years of patient calling, facing constant rejection, mockery, and abuse, Prophet Noah finally turned to Allah in desperate supplication. He asked for Allah's help and support because his people had rejected the truth. This was not a hasty prayer—it came after centuries of effort. Noah had exhausted all means of persuasion, and now he was asking Allah to intervene. This teaches us that prophets, despite their high status, were entirely dependent on Allah. It also shows that there comes a time when, after all efforts are made, we must leave the matter to Allah and trust His judgment. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) also made similar prayers when his people rejected and harmed him."
  },
  27: {
    "So We inspired him: \"Build the Ark under Our ˹watchful˺ Eyes and directions\"": "Allah answered Noah's prayer by giving him specific instructions. He was commanded to build a massive ark (ship), and this was no ordinary construction project—it was done under Allah's direct supervision and guidance. Allah watched over Noah and taught him how to build it. Imagine building a huge ship in a land with no sea nearby! His people mocked him, asking why he was building a ship on dry land. But Noah trusted Allah completely and continued his work, knowing that Allah's promise would come true.",
    "Then when Our command comes and the oven bursts ˹with water˺": "The sign for the flood to begin would be when 'the oven bursts with water.' Scholars explain this was either a specific oven that Noah had, or it refers to the earth's surface erupting with water from below. This was the signal that the punishment was starting—water would come from the sky as rain and from the earth below simultaneously, leaving no escape.",
    "take on board a pair from every species along with your family": "Noah was instructed to load the ark with a male and female of every animal species to preserve life on earth. This was a massive undertaking—gathering animals of all kinds into the ark. Additionally, he was to take his believing family members. This shows Allah's mercy in preserving life and giving the believers a means of salvation.",
    "except those against whom the decree ˹to drown˺ has already been passed": "Not all of Noah's family would be saved. His own wife and one of his sons had rejected faith and chosen to remain with the disbelievers. This is a painful lesson that faith is not inherited—each person must choose for themselves. Even being related to a prophet doesn't guarantee salvation if one rejects the truth.",
    "And do not plead with Me for those who have done wrong, for they will surely be drowned": "Allah firmly told Noah not to intercede for the wrongdoers. The time for mercy and chances had passed. They had 950 years to repent! Now the decree was final. This shows that Allah's mercy is vast, but it has limits for those who persistently reject it. There comes a point of no return for those who insist on disbelief."
  },
  28: {
    "Then when you and those with you have settled in the Ark": "Once Noah and all the believers were safely aboard the ark with the animals, settled and secure, they were to perform an act of worship. Notice Allah's care—He gave them specific words to say at this critical moment.",
    "say, \"All praise is for Allah, Who saved us from the wrongdoing people\"": "The first thing they should do upon being saved is thank Allah and praise Him. This is the attitude of believers—gratitude in times of blessing. They acknowledged that their salvation was entirely from Allah, not from their own cleverness or the ark's construction. They also recognized that those who drowned were 'wrongdoing people'—they had wronged themselves by rejecting truth. This phrase teaches us to always attribute our safety and success to Allah."
  },
  29: {
    "And pray, \"My Lord! Allow me a blessed landing\"": "Allah also taught Noah to pray for a blessed landing place. After the flood, when the water would recede, they would need a safe place to disembark and start a new life. This prayer asks Allah to make their destination blessed—full of goodness, safety, and prosperity. We can use this prayer whenever we travel or move to a new place.",
    "for You are the best accommodator": "Noah acknowledged that only Allah can provide the best landing and accommodation. No travel agent or GPS can guarantee a blessed destination—only Allah can. This phrase teaches complete reliance on Allah for our needs, recognizing that He is the ultimate provider of safety and comfort."
  },
  30: {
    "Surely in this are lessons": "Allah concludes the story by pointing out that these events contain many signs and lessons for those who reflect. The story of Noah teaches patience in calling to truth, trust in Allah's promises, the consequences of persistent disbelief, the importance of family members choosing their own faith, and Allah's power to save whom He wills and destroy whom He wills. Every generation should learn from these accounts.",
    "And We ˹always˺ put ˹people˺ to the test": "Allah reminds us that testing is a constant reality of life. Noah was tested with a rejecting people for centuries. The believers were tested with mockery and then a terrifying flood. The disbelievers were tested with a messenger and a message. Everyone faces tests—the question is how we respond. Tests reveal our true character and determine our ultimate destination."
  },
  31: {
    "Then We raised another generation after them": "After the people of Noah were destroyed in the flood, Allah caused a new generation to emerge and populate the earth. Life continued, civilizations rose, and time passed. This was the nation of 'Aad, to whom Prophet Hud was sent. Allah gives humanity chance after chance, generation after generation, always sending guidance."
  },
  32: {
    "and sent to them a messenger from among themselves": "Just as with Noah, Allah sent a messenger from within their own community—someone they knew, who spoke their language, and understood their culture. This made the message accessible and removed any excuse of not understanding.",
    "˹declaring,˺ \"Worship Allah ˹alone˺. You have no god other than Him\"": "The message was identical to Noah's message and to every prophet's message: pure monotheism. Worship Allah alone, no partners, no idols, no intermediaries. This is the core message of Islam that has never changed throughout history.",
    "Will you not then fear ˹Him˺?": "Again, the call to taqwa—consciousness of Allah that leads to avoiding His punishment and seeking His pleasure. The prophets appealed to people's reason and self-interest: why would you risk eternal punishment when guidance is right in front of you?"
  },
  33: {
    "But the chiefs of his people—who disbelieved": "Again, the opposition came from the leaders and elite. They disbelieved in Allah's oneness and rejected the messenger.",
    "denied the meeting ˹with Allah˺ in the Hereafter": "They specifically denied the resurrection and the Day of Judgment. When people don't believe in accountability after death, they feel free to do whatever they want without consequences. This denial of the afterlife is the root of much corruption.",
    "and were spoiled by the worldly luxuries We had provided for them": "Allah identifies a key problem: they were living in luxury and comfort, which made them arrogant and heedless. Wealth and ease can be a test that leads people astray if they forget the One who provided it. The nation of 'Aad was known for their physical strength, impressive buildings, and material prosperity.",
    "said ˹to the masses˺, \"This is only a human like you. He eats what you eat, and drinks what you drink\"": "Their argument was the same as Noah's people: how can a messenger be human? He eats and drinks like us! They couldn't accept that Allah would honor a regular person with prophethood. They expected messengers to be supernatural beings who don't need food or drink. This shows their misunderstanding of Allah's wisdom in sending human messengers as role models."
  },
  34: {
    "And if you ˹ever˺ obey a human like yourselves, then you would certainly be losers": "The arrogant leaders told the masses that following a human messenger would make them losers. Their pride prevented them from submitting to someone they saw as their equal. But the real loss was theirs—rejecting truth because of ego. In reality, obeying Allah's messenger is the path to success, not loss. Their definition of winning and losing was completely backward."
  },
  35: {
    "Does he promise you that once you are dead and reduced to dust and bones, you will be brought forth ˹alive˺?": "They mocked the concept of resurrection. How could decomposed bodies be brought back to life? This seemed impossible to them. They ridiculed the messenger for teaching this. Yet Allah, who created humans from nothing in the first place, can certainly recreate them. As Allah says elsewhere: 'Is not He who created the heavens and earth able to create the likes of them?' (36:81). The answer is obvious to those who reflect."
  },
  36: {
    "Impossible, simply impossible is what you are promised!": "They emphatically denied the resurrection, repeating the word 'impossible' twice for emphasis. They were absolutely certain it would never happen. This extreme confidence in their rejection shows their arrogance. They spoke as if they had complete knowledge of the unseen, when in fact they were completely ignorant of Allah's power. Many who deny the afterlife do so not based on evidence, but based on their inability to imagine it."
  },
  37: {
    "There is nothing beyond our worldly life": "This is the materialist worldview—believing that only the physical, visible world exists. They denied any spiritual reality or life after death. This belief leads to living only for worldly pleasures without concern for consequences.",
    "We die, others are born, and none will be resurrected": "They saw life as a meaningless cycle: some die, others are born, and that's it. No purpose, no accountability, no eternal consequences. This bleak worldview is actually more depressing than what they accused the messenger of teaching. Islam gives life meaning and purpose.",
    "": ""
  },
  38: {
    "He is no more than a man who has fabricated a lie about Allah": "Unable to refute the message logically, they attacked the messenger's character. They accused him of inventing lies about Allah—a serious accusation. Every prophet faced this accusation. But think about it: would a liar dedicate his entire life to a message that brought him only hardship, rejection, and persecution? The prophets gained nothing worldly from their message.",
    "and we will never believe in him": "They declared their absolute refusal to believe, closing their hearts completely. This stubborn rejection, despite clear signs and rational arguments, is what leads to punishment. Allah does not punish people for honest confusion, but for arrogant rejection of clear truth."
  },
  39: {
    "The messenger prayed, \"My Lord! Help me, because they have denied ˹me˺.\"": "Just like Noah before him, Prophet Hud turned to Allah when all efforts failed. He asked for divine help against those who rejected him. This is the same prayer Noah made (verse 26), showing that all prophets had the same relationship with Allah and faced similar challenges. When human effort is exhausted, the believer turns to Allah for support and relief."
  },
  40: {
    "Allah responded, \"Soon they will be truly regretful.\"": "Allah answered His messenger's prayer with a promise: the disbelievers would soon regret their arrogance and rejection. This regret would come when they saw the punishment approaching and realized they were wrong. But by then, it would be too late. The regret of the afterlife is the worst kind—permanent and without any chance to make amends. Allah warns us now so we can avoid that eternal regret."
  },
  41: {
    "Then the ˹mighty˺ blast overtook them with justice": "The punishment came in the form of a terrible blast or shriek—a devastating sound that destroyed them all. The phrase 'with justice' emphasizes that this was not arbitrary cruelty; it was deserved punishment after they rejected every chance to repent. Allah's punishment is always just and proportionate.",
    "and We reduced them to rubble": "The once-mighty nation of 'Aad, known for their strength and impressive constructions, was reduced to debris and ruins. Their physical power could not save them from Allah's punishment. This is a reminder that no amount of worldly strength can protect someone from Allah if He decrees their destruction.",
    "So away with the wrongdoing people!": "This expression shows Allah's rejection of the wrongdoers. They removed themselves from Allah's mercy through their own choices. The phrase serves as a warning to all future generations: this will be the fate of those who persist in wrongdoing and reject Allah's messengers."
  },
  42: {
    "Then We raised other generations after them": "History continued after the destruction of 'Aad. Allah raised new generations and civilizations, giving humanity more chances. Each generation had the opportunity to learn from those before them—but most failed to do so. This shows Allah's patience and mercy in continuously giving humanity opportunities for guidance."
  },
  43: {
    "No people can advance their doom, nor can they delay it": "Every nation has a fixed term decreed by Allah. When their time comes, nothing can speed it up or slow it down. This teaches that Allah is in complete control of history. Powerful nations that think they will last forever are mistaken—their end is already written. This should humble us and make us focus on faith rather than false security in worldly power."
  },
  44: {
    "Then We sent Our messengers in succession": "Allah sent messengers one after another throughout history—a continuous chain of guidance. No generation was left without a warner. This shows Allah's justice: He never punishes a people without first sending them clear guidance.",
    "whenever a messenger came to his people, they denied him": "Tragically, the pattern repeated itself: each nation rejected its messenger. Despite witnessing what happened to previous nations, they made the same mistakes. This is a warning against thinking 'we are different' or 'that won't happen to us.' Human arrogance tends to repeat the same errors.",
    "So We destroyed them, one after the other": "The consequence of rejection was always the same: destruction. One nation after another faced Allah's punishment. The consistency of this pattern should be a powerful warning.",
    "reducing them to ˹cautionary˺ tales": "These destroyed nations became stories told to future generations—lessons and warnings. The people of Noah, 'Aad, Thamud, and others are now known only through their tragic endings. Their wealth and power are gone; only their stories of destruction remain.",
    "So away with the people who refuse to believe!": "Again, Allah expresses His rejection of those who stubbornly refuse to believe despite clear evidence. This repetition emphasizes the seriousness of persistent disbelief."
  },
  45: {
    "Then We sent Moses and his brother Aaron": "Allah now mentions one of the greatest stories in the Quran—Prophet Moses (Musa) and his brother Aaron (Harun), peace be upon them both. Moses is the most frequently mentioned prophet in the Quran. He and Aaron were sent together as a team, supporting each other in their mission.",
    "with Our signs and compelling proof": "They were given miracles (signs) like the staff that turned into a snake, the glowing hand, and others. These were undeniable proofs of their prophethood. The 'compelling proof' refers to clear evidence and authority that should have convinced any reasonable person. Allah equipped His messengers with what they needed to fulfill their mission."
  },
  46: {
    "to Pharaoh and his chiefs": "Their mission was specifically to Pharaoh (Fir'awn), the tyrannical ruler of Egypt, and his inner circle of advisors and nobles. Pharaoh had enslaved the Children of Israel and even claimed divinity for himself, saying 'I am your lord most high' (79:24).",
    "but they behaved arrogantly": "Despite witnessing clear miracles, Pharaoh and his chiefs responded with arrogance. They refused to submit to the truth because it would mean admitting they were wrong and giving up their power and privilege. Arrogance is the barrier that prevents many from accepting truth.",
    "and were a tyrannical people": "They were oppressors who committed crimes against humanity—killing baby boys, enslaving an entire people, and spreading corruption. Their arrogance led to tyranny. When leaders reject Allah's guidance, the result is always injustice and oppression."
  },
  47: {
    "They argued, \"Will we believe in two humans, like ourselves\"": "The same old argument appears again: how can we follow human messengers? Pharaoh and his elite couldn't humble themselves to accept guidance from humans they considered beneath them. Their status and ego blinded them to the truth.",
    "whose people are slaves to us?": "They added another dimension to their arrogance: Moses and Aaron came from the enslaved Israelites. In their twisted worldview, how could slaves bring truth to masters? This racism and classism prevented them from seeing the message for what it was. But Allah chooses whom He wills for prophethood—social status means nothing to Him. In fact, it is often the humble who recognize truth while the arrogant reject it."
  },
  48: {
    "So they rejected them both": "Despite all the miracles and proofs, Pharaoh and his people chose to reject Moses and Aaron. They denied the message, persecuted the believers, and continued their oppression.",
    "and ˹so˺ were among those destroyed": "The consequence was their total destruction. Pharaoh and his army drowned in the sea when they pursued the fleeing Israelites. The same water that parted for the believers became the grave of the oppressors. Allah preserved Pharaoh's body as a sign for future generations—and indeed, his mummy remains on display to this day, a lesson for those who reflect."
  },
  49: {
    "And We certainly gave Moses the Scripture": "After saving the Children of Israel, Allah gave Moses the Torah—a complete book of guidance containing laws, teachings, and wisdom. This Scripture was meant to guide them in their new life as a free people.",
    "so perhaps his people would be ˹rightly˺ guided": "The purpose of the Scripture was guidance. Allah wanted the Israelites to live righteously and worship Him properly. Unfortunately, as history shows, many of them later deviated and disobeyed despite having clear guidance. The Scripture was a blessing, but it required people willing to follow it."
  },
  50: {
    "And We made the son of Mary and his mother a sign": "Allah mentions Prophet Jesus (Isa) by referring to him as 'the son of Mary' (Ibn Maryam), emphasizing his miraculous birth without a father. Both Jesus and Mary together are described as 'a sign'—evidence of Allah's power. Mary conceived Jesus miraculously by Allah's command, without any man touching her. This miracle proves that Allah can create however He wills. Jesus spoke as a baby to defend his mother's honor, healed the sick, and raised the dead—all by Allah's permission. Together, mother and son are among the greatest signs Allah has shown humanity.",
    "and gave them refuge on high ground—a ˹suitable˺ place for rest with flowing water": "Allah provided Mary and Jesus with a blessed place to live—elevated ground that was peaceful and had flowing water. Scholars have different opinions about where this was—some say Palestine, others say Egypt or Damascus. The key point is that Allah took care of them and provided them with a safe, comfortable place. This shows Allah's special care for His chosen servants, especially during difficult times. Mary faced harsh accusations from her people when she returned with baby Jesus, but Allah protected her and provided for her needs."
  },
  51: {
    "O messengers! Eat from what is good and lawful": "Allah addresses all His messengers collectively, commanding them to eat from pure and lawful food. This shows that all prophets—from Adam to Muhammad (peace be upon them all)—received the same basic guidance. Eating halal (lawful) and tayyib (pure, wholesome) food is not just a minor detail; it affects our spirituality and worship. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) mentioned a man who travels far, raises his hands to the sky saying 'O Lord, O Lord,' but his food is haram, his drink is haram, his clothing is from haram—how can his prayer be answered? (Muslim). What we consume matters to Allah.",
    "and act righteously": "Along with eating well, the messengers are commanded to do good deeds. There is a connection between what we consume and how we act. Pure food fuels pure actions. This command links physical nourishment with spiritual conduct—both must be pure and pleasing to Allah. Righteous actions are the fruit of true faith.",
    "Indeed, I fully know what you do": "Allah reminds even the messengers that He is fully aware of all their actions. If Allah watches the prophets, how much more should ordinary believers be conscious of His watchfulness? This awareness should motivate us to be mindful of our deeds at all times, knowing nothing is hidden from Allah."
  },
  52: {
    "Surely this religion of yours is ˹only˺ one": "All the prophets brought the same essential message: worship Allah alone and follow His guidance. Whether it was Noah, Abraham, Moses, Jesus, or Muhammad (peace be upon them all), the core religion was one—Islam, meaning submission to Allah. The details of law may have varied, but the foundation of monotheism and righteousness was always the same. This is a powerful statement of unity.",
    "and I am your Lord": "Allah declares His lordship over all of humanity across all times. There is only one God for all people—not different gods for different nations or eras. This emphasizes the universality of Allah's sovereignty.",
    "so fear Me ˹alone˺": "Since there is only one true religion and one Lord, the logical conclusion is to fear and be conscious of Him alone. Taqwa (fear and consciousness of Allah) should be directed only to Allah, not to idols, other humans, or worldly powers. This is the essence of Tawheed—directing all worship to Allah alone."
  },
  53: {
    "Yet the people have divided it into different sects": "Despite the religion being one, people broke it into fragments, creating different sects and groups. Instead of following the unified message of the prophets, they innovated, disputed, and separated. This division was not from Allah but from human ego, misunderstanding, and following desires. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) warned that his ummah would divide into many sects, and advised Muslims to stick to the main body and the way of the companions.",
    "each rejoicing in what they have": "Each sect is happy and proud of its own beliefs, thinking they alone are right. This self-satisfaction prevents them from seeking truth and unity. It is a spiritual disease—being content with falsehood or partial truth while rejecting the complete guidance. True believers should always seek authentic knowledge and be willing to accept truth from wherever it comes, rather than being blindly loyal to a group."
  },
  54: {
    "So leave them ˹O Prophet˺ in their heedlessness for a while": "Allah tells the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) to leave these stubborn people in their ignorance and confusion—but only for a limited time. This is not permission to abandon calling them to truth, but a consolation for the Prophet: don't exhaust yourself over those who refuse to listen. Allah will deal with them at the appointed time. The phrase 'for a while' is a warning that their time of reckoning will come, whether in this life or the next."
  },
  55: {
    "Do they think, since We provide them with wealth and children": "Allah questions the flawed thinking of the disbelievers. They assumed that their worldly prosperity—money and offspring—was a sign of Allah's approval and love. Many people fall into this trap: thinking that material success means they are on the right path. But this is a dangerous misunderstanding."
  },
  56: {
    "that We hasten to ˹honour˺ them ˹with˺ all kinds of good?": "They mistakenly believe that worldly blessings mean Allah is rushing to reward them with good things. But in reality, these blessings might be a test, or even a gradual leading toward punishment. Allah gives wealth to both those He loves and those He doesn't—it is not a sign of His pleasure.",
    "No! They are not aware": "Allah firmly rejects their assumption. They simply don't understand how Allah operates. Sometimes, blessings are given to test a person or to let them increase in sin before their punishment. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'When you see Allah giving a servant what he loves while he persists in sin, know that it is gradual enticement' (Ahmad). True honor is in faith and righteous deeds, not in material wealth."
  },
  57: {
    "Surely those who tremble in awe of their Lord": "Allah now describes the true believers in contrast to the heedless disbelievers. The first quality is having deep reverence and awe of Allah. These believers tremble with respectful fear—not the fear of terror, but the fear of a loving servant who dreads displeasing their beloved Master. This fear motivates them to obey Allah and avoid sin. It is the kind of fear that brings one closer to Allah, not farther away."
  },
  58: {
    "and who believe in the revelations of their Lord": "The second quality is believing in Allah's signs and revelations—the Quran and all previous scriptures in their original form. They accept the truth that Allah has sent down, without picking and choosing what suits them. Their belief is comprehensive and sincere, based on conviction and evidence, not blind following."
  },
  59: {
    "and who associate none with their Lord": "The third quality is pure monotheism—not associating any partners with Allah in worship, love, fear, or hope. They don't worship idols, saints, or any creation alongside Allah. They don't put their ultimate trust in anything other than Allah. This is the foundation of faith, and without it, no deed is accepted. Even hidden shirk (like showing off in worship) is avoided by true believers."
  },
  60: {
    "and who do whatever ˹good˺ they do with their hearts fearful": "The fourth quality is remarkable: even when doing good deeds, their hearts are filled with fear and concern. They worry whether their deeds will be accepted. Aisha (may Allah be pleased with her) asked the Prophet (peace be upon him) about this verse: 'Are these people who steal and commit adultery?' He replied: 'No, daughter of the truthful one. They are people who fast, pray, and give charity, but fear that it won't be accepted from them' (Tirmidhi). This is the balance of hope and fear that characterizes true believers.",
    "˹knowing˺ that they will return to their Lord": "Their fear stems from the certainty that they will stand before Allah and be accountable. This awareness of the meeting with Allah keeps them humble and striving. They know that ultimately, only Allah's judgment matters, so they are more concerned with His acceptance than with worldly praise."
  },
  61: {
    "it is they who race to do good deeds": "These believers with the qualities mentioned above don't delay in doing good—they rush toward it. They seize every opportunity for worship, charity, helping others, and obedience to Allah. They understand that life is short and opportunities are precious.",
    "always taking the lead": "They are at the forefront of goodness, leading the way in righteousness. While others procrastinate or hesitate, these believers are already acting. They will be among the foremost in entering Paradise, just as they were foremost in doing good. This is the description of the successful believers that Allah loves."
  },
  62: {
    "We never require of any soul more than what it can afford": "Allah reassures us that His commands are not burdensome beyond our capacity. Every obligation in Islam is within human ability. If someone genuinely cannot do something, Allah provides alternatives or exemptions. This shows Allah's mercy and justice. No one can say 'Islam is too hard'—Allah knows exactly what each person can handle.",
    "And with Us is a record which speaks the truth": "Every deed, word, and intention is recorded in a divine book that contains nothing but truth. This record will speak on the Day of Judgment, testifying for or against each person. Nothing is forgotten or overlooked. This should motivate us to be careful about what we do and say.",
    "None will be wronged": "Based on this perfect record, no one will be treated unjustly. Every good deed will be fully rewarded, and no one will be punished for what they didn't do. Allah's judgment is perfect and fair. This gives comfort to believers who may feel their efforts go unnoticed in this world—Allah sees everything and will reward accordingly."
  },
  63: {
    "But the hearts of those ˹who disbelieve˺ are oblivious to ˹all of˺ this": "In contrast to the aware believers, the disbelievers have hearts that are drowned in heedlessness. They are unaware of Allah's signs, the Day of Judgment, and the qualities of true faith just described. Their hearts are covered with layers of ignorance, desire, and distraction. They live as if there is no accountability.",
    "and they have other ˹evil˺ deeds, opposite to this, in which they are engrossed": "Not only are they missing good deeds, but they are busy with evil deeds completely opposite to the righteous actions mentioned. While believers race to do good, these people are occupied with sins, corruption, and following their desires. They are so absorbed in their wrongdoing that they have no time or interest in guidance."
  },
  64: {
    "But as soon as We seize their elite with torment, they start to cry for help": "When Allah's punishment finally strikes—whether in this world or the Hereafter—these same arrogant people who were engrossed in sin suddenly start screaming and begging for help. The 'elite' are specifically mentioned because they were the most arrogant and the leaders in disbelief. Their wealth and status cannot protect them when Allah's decree comes. Those who never cried to Allah in prayer now cry in desperation, but it is too late."
  },
  65: {
    "˹They will be told,˺ \"Do not cry for help today\"": "When they cry out, they will be told to stop—there is no point now. The time for crying to Allah was during their lives, when they could have repented and changed. Now that door is closed.",
    "Surely you will never be saved from Us": "There is no escape from Allah's punishment. No one can help them, no one can intercede for them without permission, and they have no hope of rescue. This is the terrifying reality that awaits those who persist in disbelief and sin. The same Allah they ignored is now the only one who could have saved them, but they rejected His guidance when it was offered."
  },
  66: {
    "Indeed, My revelations were recited to you": "Allah reminds them that they had every opportunity. His verses were recited to them clearly—the Quran was available, the message was delivered, warnings were given. They cannot claim ignorance.",
    "but you used to back away ˹in disgust˺": "Instead of accepting the guidance, they literally turned on their heels and walked away. They retreated from the truth, showed arrogance, and rejected the message. This physical description captures their attitude: whenever truth came, they ran in the opposite direction. Now they face the consequences of that choice."
  },
  67: {
    "boasting of the Sacred House": "The Quraysh of Makkah took pride in being the custodians of the Kaaba, the Sacred House built by Prophet Ibrahim. They used this status to feel superior, even while rejecting the very message Ibrahim brought. They honored the building but rejected its purpose—the worship of Allah alone. Religious pride without true faith is worthless.",
    "and babbling ˹nonsense about the Quran˺ by night": "They would gather at night and mock the Quran, make fun of the Prophet, and talk nonsense about the message. Instead of reflecting on its truth, they wasted their time in ridicule and idle talk. Night gatherings that should have been for worship or rest were used for sinful mockery. This is the opposite of the believers who spend their nights in prayer and remembrance of Allah."
  },
  68: {
    "Is it because they have never contemplated the Word ˹of Allah˺?": "Allah begins questioning the reasons for their rejection. Is it because they haven't truly reflected on the Quran? Deep reflection on the Quran leads to faith—those who reject it either haven't pondered it sincerely or have hardened hearts. The Quran invites people to think, reason, and reflect. If they did so honestly, they would recognize its truth.",
    "Or ˹because˺ there has come to them something that did not come to their forefathers?": "Or is it simply because this message is new to them? Their ancestors didn't receive a prophet for a long time before Muhammad (peace be upon him), so they treat this as a strange innovation. But truth doesn't become false just because previous generations didn't have it. Each generation is responsible for responding to the guidance that comes to them."
  },
  69: {
    "Or ˹because˺ they failed to recognize their Messenger, and so they denied him?": "Or is the problem that they don't recognize who Muhammad (peace be upon him) truly is? This is ironic because they knew him well! He grew up among them and they called him 'Al-Amin' (the Trustworthy) and 'As-Sadiq' (the Truthful) before prophethood. They knew his character, his honesty, and his integrity. They didn't deny him because they didn't know him—they denied him despite knowing him. Their rejection was not based on lack of information about his character."
  },
  70: {
    "Or ˹because˺ they say, \"He is insane?\"": "Or is their excuse that the Prophet is mad? This was a common accusation against prophets. But anyone who knew Muhammad (peace be upon him) knew this was absurd. An insane person doesn't produce the most eloquent and consistent book in human history, build a lasting civilization, and transform society for the better.",
    "In fact, he has come to them with the truth": "Allah refutes all their excuses. The reality is simple: Muhammad brought them the truth. The Quran is true, the message of monotheism is true, and the Day of Judgment is true. None of their objections hold water.",
    "but most of them are resentful of the truth": "Here is the real reason exposed: they simply hate the truth. It's not about logic or evidence—they dislike what the truth demands of them. The truth requires them to abandon their idols, change their lifestyle, give up their sins, and submit to Allah. Their pride and desires make them resent this. This is the root cause of most disbelief: not intellectual objections, but emotional rejection of what truth requires."
  },
  71: {
    "Had the truth followed their desires": "Allah presents a powerful argument. What if truth was based on what people wanted rather than objective reality? What if Allah changed His religion to match human whims?",
    "the heavens, the earth, and all those in them would have certainly been corrupted": "The result would be total chaos and corruption. The universe operates on fixed laws established by Allah. If everything changed based on human desires—which are contradictory, selfish, and constantly changing—nothing would function. One person wants rain, another wants sunshine; one wants to live, another wants them dead. Following desires leads to corruption, not order. This is why truth must be objective, from Allah, not subject to human preferences.",
    "In fact, We have brought them ˹the means to˺ their glory": "The Quran is actually their source of honor and glory! It elevates them, guides them to success, and gives their lives meaning. The Arabs went from being insignificant desert tribes to leaders of a world civilization because of the Quran.",
    "but they turn away from it": "Yet despite the Quran being their path to honor, they turn away from it. They reject the very thing that would benefit them most. This is the ultimate irony and tragedy of disbelief."
  },
  72: {
    "Or ˹is it because˺ you ˹O Prophet˺ are asking them for tribute?": "Allah asks another rhetorical question: maybe they reject you because you're asking them for money? Maybe they think you want to profit from this? This was not the case at all.",
    "But the reward of your Lord is best": "The Prophet (peace be upon him) never asked for payment for delivering the message. He sought his reward only from Allah, which is far better than any worldly compensation. This demonstrates his sincerity—he wasn't in it for money, power, or fame.",
    "for He is the Best Provider": "Allah is the best provider of sustenance. The Prophet trusted Allah to provide for his needs, not the contributions of his people. This should also reassure believers: when you do good for Allah's sake, He will take care of you."
  },
  73: {
    "And surely you are calling them to the Straight Path": "Allah confirms that the Prophet is inviting people to the Straight Path—the path of truth, justice, and salvation. There is nothing crooked or corrupt in this message. It leads directly to Allah's pleasure and Paradise. What the Prophet offers is genuinely good for them."
  },
  74: {
    "but those who disbelieve in the Hereafter are certainly deviating from that Path": "The root problem is identified: those who don't believe in the afterlife will inevitably deviate from the Straight Path. When someone doesn't believe in accountability after death, they have no motivation to restrain their desires or follow guidance. The belief in the Hereafter is the anchor that keeps people on the right track. Without it, people follow their whims and end up lost. This is why the Quran constantly reminds us of the Day of Judgment—it is the reality that gives meaning and direction to our lives."
  },
  75: {
    "˹Even˺ if We had mercy on them and removed their affliction": "Allah reveals His knowledge of the unseen—even if He were to show mercy and remove whatever hardship or suffering they face, it would not change their hearts. Sometimes we think that if only people's circumstances improved, they would become grateful and turn to Allah. But Allah knows the reality of hearts.",
    "they would still persist in their transgression, wandering blindly": "They would continue in their rebellion and sin, stumbling around without guidance like someone lost in darkness. Their problem is not their circumstances but their hearts. Some people use hardship as an excuse for disbelief, and others use ease as an excuse to ignore Allah. True faith is independent of circumstances. This verse shows that some hearts are so hardened that nothing will change them—not hardship and not ease."
  },
  76: {
    "And We have already seized them with torment": "Allah has already tested them with various forms of punishment and difficulty—famine, drought, loss, and other trials. These were meant to wake them up, to humble them, and to make them turn back to their Creator. Hardship is often Allah's way of calling people back to Him.",
    "but they never humbled themselves to their Lord": "Despite the trials, they refused to humble themselves before Allah. Their pride remained intact. They did not recognize that the difficulties were a call to repentance. Instead of becoming soft, their hearts became harder.",
    "nor did they ˹submissively˺ appeal ˹to Him˺": "They didn't cry out to Allah or beg Him sincerely. Even when suffering, they refused to turn to the only One who could help them. This is the height of arrogance—suffering yet refusing to ask the Creator for relief. The believer, by contrast, turns to Allah in both good times and bad, always maintaining their connection with Him."
  },
  77: {
    "But as soon as We open for them a gate of severe punishment": "The minor trials didn't humble them, so now Allah warns of something far worse—a gate of severe punishment that will be opened upon them. This could refer to punishment in this world (like what happened to previous nations) or the punishment of the Hereafter. Either way, it will be inescapable.",
    "they will be utterly desperate": "When this severe punishment comes, all their arrogance will vanish. They will be in complete despair, hopeless, with no way out. The same people who proudly refused to humble themselves will be broken and desperate. But at that point, it will be too late. This is a warning: humble yourself before Allah now, while there is still time, rather than being humbled by force when it's too late."
  },
  78: {
    "He is the One Who created for you hearing, sight, and intellect": "Allah reminds us of three of His greatest blessings: hearing, sight, and the heart (intellect/understanding). These are the tools through which we perceive the world, learn, communicate, and make decisions. Without hearing, we couldn't receive guidance. Without sight, we couldn't observe Allah's signs. Without intellect, we couldn't understand or reflect. These faculties are so precious that we cannot put a price on them, yet we often take them for granted.",
    "˹Yet˺ you hardly give any thanks": "Despite these enormous blessings, most people rarely thank Allah. We use our eyes, ears, and minds every moment, but how often do we stop to say 'Alhamdulillah' (praise be to Allah)? Gratitude is the least we owe our Creator, yet it is something most humans fail to give adequately. The Prophet (peace be upon him) would pray until his feet swelled, and when asked why when his sins were forgiven, he replied: 'Should I not be a grateful servant?' (Bukhari). True believers are characterized by gratitude."
  },
  79: {
    "And He is the One Who has dispersed you ˹all˺ over the earth": "Allah has spread humanity across the entire earth—different continents, climates, and environments. From the frozen north to the tropical equator, humans live and thrive. This dispersion is part of Allah's plan, allowing different cultures and civilizations to develop while all sharing the same origin and the same Lord.",
    "and to Him you will ˹all˺ be gathered": "No matter where you live or where you die, everyone will be gathered back to Allah on the Day of Judgment. Geography won't matter; time won't matter. Every human who ever lived will stand before Allah. This gathering is certain, and it should make us think about how we are living our lives right now."
  },
  80: {
    "And He is the One Who gives life and causes death": "Allah alone controls life and death. No doctor, no medicine, no technology can give life or prevent death when Allah decrees it. Every birth is by His permission, and every death is by His command. This should humble us and make us realize our complete dependence on Him.",
    "and to Him belongs the alternation of the day and night": "The regular cycle of day and night—which we experience every single day—is under Allah's control. The sun rises and sets on His command. This predictable cycle allows life to exist, provides time for work and rest, and demonstrates Allah's perfect management of the universe. Yet we rarely reflect on this daily miracle.",
    "Will you not then understand?": "Allah asks: after seeing all these signs of His power, will you not use your intellect? The evidence is everywhere—in your own body, in the earth, in the sky, in the cycle of day and night. Using our minds sincerely should lead us to recognize Allah's existence, power, and right to be worshipped."
  },
  81: {
    "But they ˹just˺ say what their predecessors said": "Instead of using their intellect to arrive at truth, they simply repeat what previous generations of disbelievers said. They copy the same old objections without thinking critically. This is intellectual laziness—following the crowd of deniers throughout history rather than honestly examining the evidence. Each generation of disbelievers recycles the same tired arguments."
  },
  82: {
    "They said, \"Once we are dead and reduced to dust and bones, will we really be resurrected?\"": "Their main objection is about resurrection. They find it hard to believe that decomposed bodies can be brought back to life. But this objection ignores Allah's power—the same Allah who created them from nothing the first time can certainly recreate them. As Allah says elsewhere: 'Is not He who created the heavens and earth able to create the likes of them? Yes indeed!' (36:81). The original creation from nothing is actually harder than recreation, yet they accept the first while denying the second."
  },
  83: {
    "We have already been promised this, as well as our forefathers earlier": "They mock by saying this promise of resurrection has been made before—to their ancestors—and nothing happened. They see the delay in punishment as proof that it won't happen. But Allah's timing is not like human timing. A thousand years to humans is nothing to Allah. The delay is mercy, giving time for repentance.",
    "This is nothing but ancient fables!": "They dismiss the message as myths and legends—old stories with no truth. This dismissive attitude prevents them from taking the message seriously. But labeling something as a 'fable' doesn't make it false. The truth of resurrection is backed by Allah's word, His power, and sound reasoning. Those who call it fables are the ones living in delusion."
  },
  84: {
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"To whom belong the earth and all those on it, if you ˹really˺ know?\"": "Allah instructs the Prophet to ask the disbelievers a series of questions to expose their inconsistency. The first question: who owns the earth and everything in it? This is a fundamental question about sovereignty and ownership. Even the Arab polytheists knew the answer."
  },
  85: {
    "They will reply, \"To Allah!\"": "They admit that Allah owns everything. The polytheists of Arabia never denied Allah's existence or His ultimate ownership—they just associated partners with Him in worship. This admission is used against them.",
    "Say, \"Why are you not then mindful?\"": "If you acknowledge Allah owns everything, why don't you remember this and act accordingly? Why do you worship others alongside Him? Why don't you obey Him? This question exposes their contradiction—believing in Allah's ownership while ignoring its implications."
  },
  86: {
    "˹And˺ ask ˹them˺, \"Who is the Lord of the seven heavens and the Lord of the Mighty Throne?\"": "The second question elevates the discussion to the heavens and Allah's Throne—the greatest of all created things. Who is the Lord of all this vastness and majesty? The Throne of Allah is so immense that the entire universe in comparison is like a ring thrown in a desert."
  },
  87: {
    "They will reply, \"Allah.\"": "Again, they admit that Allah is the Lord of the heavens and the Throne. They cannot deny this obvious truth.",
    "Say, \"Will you not then fear ˹Him˺?\"": "If Allah is the Lord of such magnificent creation, shouldn't you fear Him and obey Him? How can you acknowledge His supreme lordship but then disobey Him and worship others? Fear of Allah should naturally follow from recognizing His majesty and power."
  },
  88: {
    "Ask ˹them also,˺ \"In Whose Hands is the authority over all things\"": "The third question addresses absolute authority and control. Who has complete dominion over everything that exists?",
    "protecting ˹all˺ while none can protect against Him": "Allah protects whomever He wills, and no one can override His protection. Conversely, if Allah decrees something for someone, no one can protect that person from Allah. This shows His complete and unchallenged authority. No idol, no saint, no power can help you if Allah decides otherwise.",
    "if you ˹really˺ know?": "The question challenges them to use their knowledge—they already know the answer."
  },
  89: {
    "They will reply, \"Allah.\"": "Once again, they have no choice but to admit the truth—Allah holds absolute authority.",
    "Say, \"How are you then so deluded?\"": "After admitting all of this—that Allah owns everything, is Lord of the heavens, and has absolute authority—how can you be so deluded as to worship others? How can you deny resurrection when the One with all power has promised it? The word 'deluded' suggests they are under a spell of misguidance. Their contradiction is irrational and inexcusable."
  },
  90: {
    "In fact, We have brought them the truth": "Allah declares that the message brought to them is the absolute truth—not myths, not fables, not the fabrications they accuse the Prophet of. The Quran is truth from the Lord of all worlds.",
    "and they are certainly liars": "Those who reject this truth and make false claims about Allah, the Prophet, or the message are liars. They lie when they call the Quran fables. They lie when they claim resurrection won't happen. They lie when they worship idols while admitting Allah's supreme authority. Their entire worldview is built on lies and contradictions."
  },
  91: {
    "Allah has never had ˹any˺ offspring": "Allah categorically denies having any children. This refutes the beliefs of those who claim Allah has sons or daughters—whether the Arab polytheists who claimed the angels were Allah's daughters, or Christians who claim Jesus is the son of God. Allah is self-sufficient and has no need for offspring. Having children implies need, weakness, or incompleteness—none of which apply to Allah.",
    "nor is there any god besides Him": "There is no other deity besides Allah. This is the core of Tawheed. All other objects of worship—idols, humans, angels, nature—are false gods with no power.",
    "Otherwise, each god would have taken away what he created": "Allah presents a logical argument. If there were multiple gods, each would have their own creation and domain. They would not share power peacefully.",
    "and they would have tried to dominate one another": "Multiple gods would inevitably conflict with each other, each trying to overpower the others. The universe would be in chaos with competing divine wills. But we see perfect order in creation, proving there is only one supreme authority running everything. This is called the 'argument from order' or 'burhan al-tamanu' (proof of mutual hindrance).",
    "Glorified is Allah above what they claim!": "Allah is far above and free from all the false things they attribute to Him—whether partners, children, or any deficiency. He is perfect and unique."
  },
  92: {
    "˹He is the˺ Knower of the seen and unseen": "Allah's knowledge encompasses everything—what is visible and what is hidden, what is present and what is absent, what has happened and what will happen. Nothing escapes His knowledge. This is another attribute that belongs to Allah alone—no idol, no human, no creation knows the unseen.",
    "Exalted is He above what they associate ˹with Him˺": "Allah is far above any partner they associate with Him. How can they compare created things with limited knowledge to the Creator who knows everything? The comparison is absurd, and Allah rejects it completely."
  },
  93: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"My Lord! Should You show me what they are threatened with\"": "Allah teaches the Prophet a prayer to make. The Prophet is instructed to ask Allah that if he lives to see the punishment promised to the disbelievers come upon them, he should be protected from it. This acknowledges that punishment will come—the only question is whether the Prophet will witness it in his lifetime."
  },
  94: {
    "then, my Lord, do not count me among the wrongdoing people": "The Prophet asks not to be included among the wrongdoers when punishment descends. This prayer shows humility—even the Prophet, who is guaranteed Paradise, is taught to seek Allah's protection. It also teaches believers to always fear being associated with wrongdoers and to seek refuge from punishment, regardless of how righteous we think we are."
  },
  95: {
    "We are indeed able to show you what We have threatened them with": "Allah affirms His ability to make the Prophet witness the punishment of the disbelievers. Allah can bring the punishment at any time—nothing prevents Him. Some of this came true in the Prophet's lifetime, such as the defeat of the Quraysh at the Battle of Badr, and more came after his death. Allah's promises always come true."
  },
  96: {
    "Respond to evil with what is best": "Allah gives the Prophet—and by extension all believers—a golden principle: when faced with evil treatment, respond with what is best, not with equal evil. This doesn't mean accepting injustice, but rather maintaining noble character even when mistreated. When someone insults you, respond with patience or kind words. When someone wrongs you, don't sink to their level. This response often transforms enemies into friends and earns Allah's pleasure.",
    "We know well what they claim": "Allah assures the Prophet that He knows everything the disbelievers say and do. Nothing escapes Him. The Prophet doesn't need to take revenge—Allah will handle them. This brings comfort: we don't have to respond to every attack because Allah sees everything and will bring justice."
  },
  97: {
    "And say, \"My Lord! I seek refuge in You from the temptations of the devils\"": "Allah teaches the Prophet another essential prayer: seeking refuge from the whispers and incitements of devils. Shaytan (Satan) and his helpers constantly try to mislead humans—provoking anger, despair, sin, and deviation. The best protection is seeking Allah's refuge. This prayer is recommended before reading Quran and in many situations where one might be vulnerable to satanic influence."
  },
  98: {
    "And I seek refuge in You, my Lord, that they ˹even˺ come near me": "The prayer continues: asking Allah for protection from devils even being present around him. This is a comprehensive prayer for protection—not just from their whispers, but from their very presence. Believers should make this prayer regularly, especially before sleeping, before entering bathrooms, during anger, and in other vulnerable moments. The devils are a real enemy, and only Allah can truly protect us from them."
  },
  99: {
    "When death approaches any of them, they cry, \"My Lord! Let me go back\"": "At the moment of death, when the disbeliever sees the angels of death and realizes the truth of everything they denied, they desperately beg to be sent back to the world. Suddenly, all their arrogance disappears. They now believe in Allah, in death, in resurrection—but it's too late. This is a terrifying scene: someone who spent their life denying Allah now begging for just one more chance. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Allah accepts the repentance of a servant as long as his soul has not reached his throat' (Tirmidhi). Once death begins, the door of repentance closes."
  },
  100: {
    "so I may do good in what I left behind": "They promise to do good deeds if given another chance. They would pray, give charity, believe properly, and fix their mistakes. Everyone makes these promises at death. But Allah knows the truth—if they were sent back, most would return to their old ways. As Allah says elsewhere: 'If they were sent back, they would return to what they were forbidden' (6:28). Their regret is not sincere repentance but desperate fear of punishment.",
    "Never! It is only a ˹useless˺ appeal they make": "Allah firmly rejects their request with the word 'Kalla!'—meaning absolutely not, never! This is just empty talk, meaningless words that will not be accepted. The time for action was during their life. Now, words alone are worthless. This should be a powerful wake-up call for the living: act now while you can, because at death, promises mean nothing.",
    "And there is a barrier behind them until the Day they are resurrected": "After death, there is a 'barzakh'—a barrier or realm between this world and the Day of Judgment. The dead cannot return to the world. They remain in this intermediate state, experiencing either the bliss of their grave (for believers) or its torment (for disbelievers), until the Day of Resurrection. This barzakh makes return impossible. The souls are held there, unable to come back to fix their mistakes or warn their loved ones. This is why every moment of life is precious—once death comes, the opportunity is gone forever."
  },
  101: {
    "Then, when the Trumpet will be blown": "The Trumpet (Sur) is a massive horn that the angel Israfil will blow to signal the end of this world and the beginning of the Day of Judgment. The first blow will cause all living things to die, and the second blow will resurrect everyone for judgment. This is a cataclysmic event that marks the transition from this temporary world to the eternal realm of accountability.",
    "there will be no kinship between them on that Day": "On that Day, family ties and lineage will mean nothing. In this world, people take pride in their ancestry, rely on family connections, and expect relatives to help them. But on the Day of Judgment, no one's family name or tribal affiliation will benefit them. A person's father being a prophet won't help them if they disbelieved. Your children, parents, and spouse cannot save you. Only your own deeds matter.",
    "nor will they ˹even care to˺ ask about one another": "People will be so overwhelmed with their own situation that they won't even think to ask about their loved ones. Everyone will be focused on themselves, terrified about their own fate. As Allah says elsewhere: 'The Day a man will flee from his brother, and his mother and his father, and his wife and his children—each one of them that Day will have enough concern of his own' (80:34-37). The only thing that will matter is one's relationship with Allah and one's record of deeds."
  },
  102: {
    "As for those whose scale is heavy ˹with good deeds˺": "On the Day of Judgment, deeds will be weighed on a real scale. This scale has two sides—one for good deeds and one for bad deeds. Those whose good deeds outweigh their bad deeds will have a 'heavy' scale. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Two words are light on the tongue, heavy on the scale, and beloved to the Most Merciful: SubhanAllahi wa bihamdihi, SubhanAllahil Azeem' (Bukhari). Even small good deeds can carry tremendous weight with Allah.",
    "it is they who will be successful": "This is the ultimate success—success on the Day when it matters most. All the worldly definitions of success—wealth, fame, power—become meaningless. The only real success is having your good deeds outweigh your bad deeds and being admitted to Paradise. This is what the surah opened with: 'Successful indeed are the believers' (verse 1). Now we see the culmination of that success."
  },
  103: {
    "But those whose scale is light": "Those whose bad deeds outweigh their good deeds—or who have no good deeds at all due to disbelief—will have a 'light' scale. Their good deeds were too few, insincere, or canceled out by their sins and disbelief.",
    "they will have doomed themselves": "They are the true losers. They lost themselves—the most precious thing they had. They traded eternal happiness for temporary pleasures. They had the chance to believe and do good but wasted it. No one wronged them; they wronged themselves.",
    "staying in Hell forever": "Their abode is Hell, and for the disbelievers, it is eternal. There is no escape, no end, no relief. This is the consequence of rejecting Allah's guidance and persisting in sin. The permanence of this punishment should terrify anyone who reflects on it and motivate them to change now while they still can."
  },
  104: {
    "The Fire will burn their faces": "Allah describes the horrific punishment: the fire will scorch their faces. The face is the most honorable part of the human body—it's how we are recognized, how we express ourselves, the part we most protect. In Hell, this honored part will be directly exposed to flames.",
    "leaving them deformed": "Their faces will be disfigured, distorted with lips pulled back from teeth in a hideous grimace of agony. The Arabic word 'kalihoon' describes a face twisted in pain, like the expression of extreme suffering. This graphic description is meant to make us fear this fate and work to avoid it through faith and good deeds."
  },
  105: {
    "˹It will be said,˺ \"Were My revelations not recited to you\"": "While they suffer, they will be questioned and reminded. Allah's verses were recited to them—the Quran was available, the message was delivered, warnings were given repeatedly. They cannot claim they didn't know.",
    "but you used to deny them?": "Despite hearing the truth, they chose to reject it. They called it lies, fables, and the words of a madman. Now they face the consequences of that denial. This question increases their anguish—they know they had every opportunity but threw it away."
  },
  106: {
    "They will cry, \"Our Lord! Our ill-fate took hold of us\"": "Now they confess and try to explain themselves. They blame their own wretchedness and misfortune, acknowledging that they were overcome by their own bad nature and choices. This is actually an admission of guilt disguised as an excuse. They recognize they were wrong.",
    "so we became a misguided people": "They admit they were misguided—astray from the truth. But this admission comes too late. In this life, they proudly rejected guidance. Now, in the face of punishment, they acknowledge what they denied. If only they had admitted this sooner and sought guidance while it could benefit them."
  },
  107: {
    "Our Lord! Take us out of this ˹Fire˺": "They desperately beg to be removed from Hell. The same people who arrogantly rejected Allah now plead with Him. They want another chance, just like they begged at the moment of death. The punishment has humbled them completely.",
    "Then if we ever return ˹to denial˺, we will truly be wrongdoers": "They promise that if given another chance, they would never return to disbelief. If they did, they would be admitting themselves to be wrongdoers. This seems like sincere repentance, but Allah knows the reality of hearts. As mentioned earlier, Allah says if they were sent back, they would return to their old ways (6:28). Their repentance is born of punishment, not genuine love for truth."
  },
  108: {
    "Allah will respond, \"Be despised in there!\"": "Allah's response is devastating. 'Ikhsa'oo' is a word used to drive away dogs—it means be despised, be humiliated, get away. After all their pleas and promises, Allah rejects them with contempt. They who were arrogant in this world are now treated with utter disgrace.",
    "Do not ˹ever˺ plead with Me ˹again˺!": "They are forbidden from even speaking to Allah again. The door of communication is permanently closed. In this life, Allah invited them to call upon Him, but they refused. Now they want to call upon Him, but He refuses to listen. This is perhaps the most terrifying aspect of their punishment—complete and permanent rejection by their Creator."
  },
  109: {
    "Indeed, there was a group of My servants who used to pray": "Allah reminds them of the believers they used to mock. These were humble servants of Allah who would sincerely pray and supplicate to their Lord.",
    "'Our Lord! We have believed, so forgive us and have mercy on us'": "The believers' prayer was beautiful in its simplicity: acknowledging their faith, asking for forgiveness for their shortcomings, and requesting Allah's mercy. They recognized their need for Allah despite their belief and good deeds.",
    "'for You are the best of those who show mercy'": "They affirmed Allah's supreme mercy, knowing that only His mercy could save them. This prayer shows the humility and hope of true believers—they don't rely on their deeds alone but on Allah's boundless mercy."
  },
  110: {
    "but you were ˹so busy˺ making fun of them": "Instead of joining these righteous people or at least respecting them, the disbelievers mocked them. They ridiculed their prayers, their modest lifestyle, their faith, and their hope in the Hereafter. Making fun of religious people was their entertainment.",
    "that it made you forget My remembrance": "Their mockery of believers became so consuming that it distracted them from remembering Allah altogether. They were so busy laughing at the faithful that they neglected their own relationship with Allah. Mockery of religion is not just offensive—it's spiritually destructive to the mocker.",
    "And you used to laugh at them": "They laughed at the believers, considering them foolish and backward. But now the tables have turned. The believers are in Paradise, and the mockers are in Hell. As Allah says: 'So Today those who believed are laughing at the disbelievers' (83:34). The last laugh belongs to the believers."
  },
  111: {
    "Today I have indeed rewarded them for their perseverance": "Allah announces that He has rewarded the believers for their patience. They were patient in worship, patient in avoiding sins, and patient in bearing the mockery and persecution of disbelievers. Their patience has been recognized and recompensed.",
    "they are certainly the triumphant": "The believers are declared the ultimate winners. They won because they stayed firm despite difficulties. They won because they prioritized the eternal over the temporary. They won because they trusted Allah's promise. This is the victory that matters—not worldly success, but triumph on the Day of Judgment."
  },
  112: {
    "He will ask ˹them˺, \"How many years did you remain on earth?\"": "Allah will question the people of Hell about how long they spent in the worldly life. This question is meant to make them reflect on how they wasted their time. They had decades—perhaps 60, 70, 80 years—to believe and do good, but they squandered it."
  },
  113: {
    "They will reply, \"We remained ˹only˺ a day or part of a day\"": "Compared to the eternity they now face, their entire worldly life seems like nothing—just a day or even less. When facing forever in Hell, 80 years feels like a few hours. This is the reality of time: what seemed long while living it feels incredibly short in retrospect.",
    "But ask those who kept count": "They are so disoriented by the reality of their situation that they cannot even accurately recall their lifespan. They suggest asking those who kept records. This shows their confusion and the overwhelming nature of facing eternal consequences for a brief life poorly spent."
  },
  114: {
    "He will say, \"You only remained for a little while\"": "Allah confirms their assessment—yes, their worldly life was indeed very short. Even if you live 100 years, it is nothing compared to eternity. The brevity of life is a truth most people ignore while living but fully realize when it's too late.",
    "if only you knew": "If only they had understood this while alive! If they had truly internalized how short life is and how long eternity is, they would have made different choices. They would have prioritized the permanent over the temporary. This is a lesson for the living: understand now that this life is short, and invest in your eternal future."
  },
  115: {
    "Did you then think that We had created you without purpose": "This is a profound rhetorical question. Did they think their existence was meaningless—just random chance with no purpose? The idea that the magnificent creation of the human being was purposeless is absurd. Allah created humans for a noble purpose: to know Him, worship Him, and be tested in this life.",
    "and that you would never be returned to Us?": "Did they think there would be no accountability, no return to the Creator? This belief—that life ends at death with no consequences—is what led them astray. The purpose of creation is intimately connected to the return to Allah. Life is a test, and the test must have results. Denying the return makes life seem meaningless and removes moral accountability."
  },
  116: {
    "Exalted is Allah, the True King!": "After exposing the foolishness of those who denied purpose and resurrection, Allah declares His own exaltation. He is the True King—the only real sovereign, unlike false gods and worldly kings who have no real power. His kingship is absolute and eternal.",
    "There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him": "This is the declaration of Tawheed—the central message of Islam and of this entire surah. All the stories, arguments, and warnings lead to this truth: only Allah deserves worship.",
    "the Lord of the Honourable Throne": "Allah is the Lord of the Throne, which is the greatest of all created things, encompassing the entire universe. The Throne is described as 'honorable' or 'noble,' reflecting the majesty of its Lord. This emphasizes Allah's supreme authority over all creation."
  },
  117: {
    "Whoever invokes, besides Allah, another god—for which they can have no proof": "Anyone who calls upon, worships, or prays to any deity besides Allah is committing the worst sin without any evidence or justification. There is no proof—logical, scriptural, or experiential—that any false god deserves worship. All the proofs point to Allah alone.",
    "they will surely find their penalty with their Lord": "Such a person will face accountability before Allah. Their reckoning awaits them, and they will have to answer for their shirk (associating partners with Allah). This is not a threat to be taken lightly—it is a certainty.",
    "Indeed, the disbelievers will never succeed": "The surah opened by declaring that the believers are successful. Now it closes by declaring that the disbelievers will never succeed. No matter what they achieve in this world—wealth, power, fame—they are ultimate failures if they die in disbelief. Success and failure are defined by one's relationship with Allah."
  },
  118: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"My Lord! Forgive and have mercy\"": "The surah ends with a beautiful prayer that the Prophet is commanded to make—and by extension, all believers should make. It asks for two things: forgiveness (maghfirah) for our sins and shortcomings, and mercy (rahmah) to cover us with Allah's blessings and protection. This combination acknowledges that we are sinners in need of forgiveness and weak servants in need of mercy.",
    "for You are the best of those who show mercy": "The prayer ends by praising Allah as the best of those who show mercy. This is the same phrase used by the believers whom the disbelievers used to mock (verse 109). It acknowledges that while others may show mercy, Allah's mercy is supreme, unlimited, and perfect. Ending the surah with this prayer teaches us to always conclude with hope in Allah's mercy, no matter how stern the warnings that preceded. Islam balances fear of punishment with hope in mercy, and this prayer embodies that balance beautifully. The believer should never despair of Allah's mercy, for 'He is the best of those who show mercy.'"
  }
};